<subsection xml:id="subsec-writing-experimental-probability-outcomes-in-different-situations">
    <title>Writing experimental probability outcomes in different situations</title>
    <p>
        Writing experimental probability outcomes" means recording the results of an experiment by noting how many times a specific event occurred out of a total number of trials essentially expressing the probability of that event happening based on the actual data collected during the experiment, rather than theoretical calculations.
    </p>
    <p>
        It's usually written as a fraction, decimal, or percentage where the numerator is the number of times the event occurred and the denominator is the total number of trials. 
    </p>
    <p>
        <m>\textbf{Key points about experimental probability outcomes:}</m>
    </p>
    <p>
        <ul>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Based on real data:
                </p>
                <p>
                    Unlike theoretical probability, which relies on mathematical calculations, experimental probability is based on the actual outcomes observed in an experiment. 
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Calculated as a ratio:
                </p>
                <p>
                    To write an experimental probability, you divide the number of times the event occurred by the total number of trials. 
                </p>
            </li>
        </ul>
    </p>
    <p>
        Mathematically, the formula for the experimental probability is defined by;
    </p>
    <p>
        <m>\textbf{Probability of an Event P(E) = Number of times an event occurs / Total number of trials.}</m>
    </p>
