    <p>
        Learning point
    </p>
    <p>
        Suppose you spin a spinner seven times and the arrow stops at <m>3</m> four times:
    </p>
    <p>
        The experimental probability that the arrow will point to <m>3</m> is given by:
    </p>
    <p>
        <m>\textbf{Probability}</m><m>(3)</m> = <m>\frac{4}{7}</m>
    </p>
    <p>
        Therefore, <m>\textbf{experimental probability}</m> = <m>\frac{\textbf{number of outcomes}}{\textbf{total number of trials'}}</m>
    </p>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A bag contains three red balls and two green balls. If a ball is picked from the bag at random, list all the possible outcomes.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Possible outcomes are; <m>\textbf{red, red, red, green and green.}</m>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
